Former president Jacob Zuma's lawyers and co-accused French Arms firm, Thales, will continue their fight for a permanent stay of prosecution in their corruption case on Thursday. • Editor’s note: Livestream above courtesy DStv 403. You can also watch it on DStv Now. PIETERMARITZBURG - Former president Jacob Zuma's lawyers and co-accused French Arms firm, Thales, will continue their fight for a permanent stay of prosecution in their corruption case on Thursday. The state's expected to argue against their application. Zuma returned to court this week with a new legal team. READ: Zuma claims charges against him a 'political ploy' The former president is facing numerous charges, including racketeering, money laundering and corruption. The charges relate to payments he allegedly received as a bribe to protect arms company Thales from an investigation into the controversial multibillion-rand arms deal. Zuma has previously dismissed the claims against him as propaganda.